	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have no official word on this whatsoever, so these are just my thoughts.&nbsp;&nbsp;When EQ first started, online games were a new market.  But today that market is huge.  There are a lot of online games out there and a lot more slated to come out just over the horizon.  I feel that Sony is making EQ easier to play to draw in more customers.  The percentage of “casual players” has grown by leaps and bounds as online games have made their into the mainstream.  Sony wants its share of that customer base.  Look at all the changes that have been introduced with other recent patches and the new expansions.  Many of them are designed to make the game easier to play.  The perfect example of this are all the port books that appeared with the Planes of Power expansion.  Traveling across the face of Norrath has never been easier.  The inability to check on items on the net, or use such programs as ICQ, has always been a pain.  Making the net accessible during game play will make a lot of people happy.  I agree that doing so is opening a Pandora’s box of possible problems, but Sony has always bee very good about dealing with troublemakers.  If people try to use third party programs to cheat, I have no doubt Sony will do their best to ban them from the game.  Personally, I don’t feel any kind of cheat program is worth the risk of never being able to play the game again.  If Sony continues to enforce their ToS, as they have enthusiastically done thus far, then I feel that will be a sufficient deterrent for most people.  And for those who do try to cheat, I hope they enjoy playing DAoC.  <br><br>&nbsp;<br><b>Pait Spiritwalker</b><br>Vah Shir Shaman, 55th Season<br><b>Namir Shadowstalker</b><br>Wood Elf Ranger, 51st Season<br><b>Calabar Silverthorn</b><br>Wood Elf Druid, 51st Season<br><br><b>Seventh Hammer</b> </td></tr>
